# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-cloudtrail
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] COSO updated their standards accordingly.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] As companies began efforts to comply with these regulations, the interconnectedness of governance, risk management, and compliance became clear.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] This created a market for training and software to bring these function together; for example, in 2002, Symbiant, a UK software development company, created the first GRC software that let teams work together online, combining risk registers, evaluations and audit tracking all in one system.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] The term "Governance, risk, and compliance" or "GRC" was published by Scott Mitchell, founder of the Open Compliance and Ethics Group (OCEG), in an academic paper in 2007.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] Governance, risk, and compliance (GRC) are three related facets that aim to assure an organization reliably achieves objectives, addresses uncertainty and acts with integrity.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] Governance, risk and compliance (GRC) is a discipline that aims to synchronize information and activity across governance, and compliance in order to operate more efficiently, enable effective information sharing, more effectively report activities and avoid wasteful overlaps.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] If not integrated and instead tackled in a traditional "silo" approach, most organizations must sustain unmanageable numbers of GRC-related requirements due to changes in technology, increasing data storage, market globalization and increased regulation.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] Specific fields have developed GRC approaches; there is financial GRC (aka FinGRC), Legal GRC, and Operational GRC.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] As companies have begun to adopt artificial intelligence to help run their businesses, the risks intrinsic to AI raise GRC challenges to the companies using AI products.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/governance-risk-management-and-compliance] As of 2025, some companies were beginning to adopt AI tools to help them manage GRC.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] An **information security audit** is an audit of the level of information security in an organization.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] It is an independent review and examination of system records, activities, and related documents.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] These audits are intended to improve the level of information security, avoid improper information security designs, and optimize the efficiency of the security safeguards and security processes.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Within the broad scope of auditing information security there are multiple types of audits, multiple objectives for different audits, etc.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Most commonly the controls being audited can be categorized as technical, physical and administrative.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Auditing information security covers topics from auditing the physical security of data centers to auditing the logical security of databases, and highlights key components to look for and different methods for auditing these areas.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] When centered on the Information technology (IT) aspects of information security, it can be seen as a part of an information technology audit.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] It is often then referred to as an information technology security audit or a computer security audit.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] However, information security encompasses much more than IT.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The auditor is responsible for assessing the current technological maturity level of a company during the first stage of the audit.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] This stage is used to assess the current status of the company and helps identify the required time, cost and scope of an audit.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The auditor should plan a company's audit based on the information found in the previous step.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Planning an audit helps the auditor obtain sufficient and appropriate evidence for each company's specific circumstances.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] It helps predict audit costs at a reasonable level, assign the proper manpower and time line and avoid misunderstandings with clients.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] An auditor should be adequately educated about the company and its critical business activities before conducting a data center review.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The objective of the data center is to align data center activities with the goals of the business while maintaining the security and integrity of critical information and processes.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] In the next step, the auditor outlines the objectives of the audit after that conducting a review of a corporate data center takes place.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Auditors consider multiple factors that relate to data center procedures and activities that potentially identify audit risks in the operating environment and assess the controls in place that mitigate those risks.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] After thorough testing and analysis, the auditor is able to adequately determine if the data center maintains proper controls and is operating efficiently and effectively.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The next step is to collect evidence to satisfy data center audit objectives.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] This involves traveling to the data center location and observing processes within the data center.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] After the audit examination is completed, the audit findings and suggestions for corrective actions can be communicated to responsible stakeholders in a formal meeting.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] This ensures better understanding and support of the audit recommendations.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] It also gives the audited organization an opportunity to express its views on the issues raised.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Writing a report after such a meeting and describing where agreements have been reached on all audit issues can greatly enhance audit effectiveness.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Exit conferences also help finalize recommendations that are practical and feasible.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The data center review report should summarize the auditor's findings and be similar in format to a standard review report.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The review report should be dated as of the completion of the auditor's inquiry and procedures.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] It should state what the review entailed and explain that a review provides only "limited assurance" to third parties.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Typically, a data center review report consolidates the entirety of the audit.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] It also offers recommendations surrounding proper implementation of physical safeguards and advises the client on appropriate roles and responsibilities of its personnel.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The report may optionally include rankings of the security vulnerabilities identified throughout the performance of the audit and the urgency of the tasks necessary to address them.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Rankings like "high", "low", and "medium" can be used to describe the imperativeness of the tasks.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] In certain regulated industries, information security audits may be mandated by law.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The Office for Civil Rights (OCR) within HHS enforces these requirements and has cited the failure to conduct an adequate risk analysis as one of the most common findings in HIPAA enforcement actions.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] To assist organizations in meeting these requirements, the Office of the National Coordinator for Health Information Technology (ONC) and OCR developed a free Security Risk Assessment Tool for small and medium-sized healthcare practices.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Information Security Officer (ISO) is a relatively new position, which has emerged in organizations to deal in the aftermath of chaotic growth in information technology and network communication.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The role of the ISO has been very nebulous since the problem that they were created to address was not defined clearly.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The role of an ISO has become one of following the dynamics of the security environment and keeping the risk posture balanced for the organization.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Information systems audits combine the efforts and skill sets from the accounting and technology fields.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Professionals from both fields rely on one another to ensure the security of the information and data.With this collaboration, the security of the information system has proven to increase over time.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] In relation to the information systems audit, the role of the auditor is to examine the company's controls of the security program.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Furthermore, the auditor discloses the operating effectiveness of these controls in an audit report.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The Information Systems Audit and Control Association (ISACA), an Information Technology professional organization, promotes gaining expertise through various certifications.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The benefits of these certifications are applicable to external and internal personnel of the system.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The auditor should ask certain questions to better understand the network and its vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The auditor should first assess the extent of the network is and how it is structured.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] A network diagram can assist the auditor in this process.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The next question an auditor should ask is what critical information this network must protect.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Things such as enterprise systems, mail servers, web servers, and host applications accessed by customers are typically areas of focus.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] It is also important to know who has access and to what parts.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Do customers and vendors have access to systems on the network?
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Can employees access information from home?
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Lastly, the auditor should assess how the network is connected to external networks and how it is protected.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Most networks are at least connected to the internet, which could be a point of vulnerability.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] These are critical questions in protecting networks.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] When you have a function that deals with money either incoming or outgoing it is very important to make sure that duties are segregated to minimize and hopefully prevent fraud.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] One of the key ways to ensure proper segregation of duties (SoD) from a systems perspective is to review individuals' access authorizations.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] For complex systems such as SAP, it is often preferred to use tools developed specifically to assess and analyze SoD conflicts and other types of system activity.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] For other systems or for multiple system formats you should monitor which users may have superuser access to the system giving them unlimited access to all aspects of the system.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Also, developing a matrix for all functions highlighting the points where proper segregation of duties has been breached will help identify potential material weaknesses by cross-checking each employee's available accesses.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] This is as important if not more so in the development function as it is in production.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Ensuring that people who develop the programs are not the ones who are authorized to pull it into production is key to preventing unauthorized programs into the production environment where they can be used to perpetrate fraud.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] In assessing the need for a client to implement encryption policies for their organization, the Auditor should conduct an analysis of the client's risk and data value.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Companies with multiple external users, e-commerce applications, and sensitive customer/employee information should maintain rigid encryption policies aimed at encrypting the correct data at the appropriate stage in the data collection process.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Auditors should continually evaluate their client's encryption policies and procedures.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Companies that are heavily reliant on e-commerce systems and wireless networks are extremely vulnerable to theft and loss of critical information in transmission.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Policies and procedures should be documented and carried out to ensure that all transmitted data is protected.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The auditor should verify that management has controls in place over the data encryption management process.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Access to keys should require dual control, keys should be composed of two separate components and should be maintained on a computer that is not accessible to programmers or outside users.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Furthermore, management should attest that encryption policies ensure data protection at the desired level and verify that the cost of encrypting the data does not exceed the value of the information itself.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] All data that is required to be maintained for an extensive amount of time should be encrypted and transported to a remote location.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Procedures should be in place to guarantee that all encrypted sensitive information arrives at its location and is stored properly.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Finally, the auditor should attain verification from management that the encryption system is strong, not attackable, and compliant with all local and international laws and regulations.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Just as it sounds, a logical security audit follows a format in an organized procedure.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The first step in an audit of any system is to seek to understand its components and its structure.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] When auditing logical security the auditor should investigate what security controls are in place, and how they work.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Network security is achieved by various tools including firewalls and proxy servers, encryption, logical security and access controls, anti-virus software, and auditing systems such as log management.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Firewalls are a very basic part of network security.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] They are often placed between the private local network and the internet.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Firewalls provide a flow-through for traffic in which it can be authenticated, monitored, logged, and reported.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Some different types of firewalls include network layer firewalls, screened subnet firewalls, packet filter firewalls, dynamic packet filtering firewalls, hybrid firewalls, transparent firewalls, and application-level firewalls.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The process of encryption involves converting plain text into a series of unreadable characters known as the ciphertext.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] If the encrypted text is stolen or attained while in transit, the content is unreadable to the viewer.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] This guarantees secure transmission and is extremely useful to companies sending/receiving critical information.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Once encrypted information arrives at its intended recipient, the decryption process is deployed to restore the ciphertext back to plaintext.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Proxy servers hide the true address of the client workstation and can also act as a firewall.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Proxy server firewalls have special software to enforce authentication.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Proxy server firewalls act as a middle man for user requests.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Antivirus software programs such as McAfee and Symantec software locate and dispose of malicious content.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] These virus protection programs run live updates to ensure they have the latest information about known computer viruses.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Logical security includes software safeguards for an organization's systems, including user ID and password access, authentication, access rights and authority levels.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] These measures are to ensure that only authorized users are able to perform actions or access information in a network or a workstation.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Vulnerabilities in an organization's IT systems are often not attributed to technical weaknesses, but rather related to individual behavior of employees within the organization.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] A simple example of this is users leaving their computers unlocked or being vulnerable to phishing attacks.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] As a result, a thorough InfoSec audit will frequently include a penetration test in which auditors attempt to gain access to as much of the system as possible, from both the perspective of a typical employee as well as an outsider.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] A behavioral audit ensures preventative measures are in place such as a phishing webinar, where employees are made aware of what phishing is and how to detect it.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] System and process assurance audits combine elements from IT infrastructure and application/information security audits and use diverse controls in categories such as Completeness, Accuracy, Validity (V) and Restricted access (CAVR).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] When it comes to programming it is important to ensure proper physical and password protection exists around servers and mainframes for the development and update of key systems.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Having physical access security at one's data center or office such as electronic badges and badge readers, security guards, choke points, and security cameras is vitally important to ensuring the security of applications and data.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Then one needs to have security around changes to the system.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Those usually have to do with proper security access to make the changes and having proper authorization procedures in place for pulling programming changes from development through test and finally into production.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] With processing, it is important that procedures and monitoring of a few different aspects such as the input of falsified or erroneous data, incomplete processing, duplicate transactions and untimely processing are in place.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Making sure that input is randomly reviewed or that all processing has proper approval is a way to ensure this.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] It is important to be able to identify incomplete processing and ensure that proper procedures are in place for either completing it or deleting it from the system if it was in error.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] There should also be procedures to identify and correct duplicate entries.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Finally, when it comes to processing that is not being done on a timely basis one should back-track the associated data to see where the delay is coming from and identify whether or not this delay creates any control concerns.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Finally, access, it is important to realize that maintaining network security against unauthorized access is one of the major focuses for companies as threats can come from a few sources.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] First, one has internal unauthorized access.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] It is very important to have system access passwords that must be changed regularly and that there is a way to track access and changes so one is able to identify who made what changes.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The second arena to be concerned with is remote access, people accessing one's system from the outside through the internet.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] Setting up firewalls and password protection to on-line data changes are key to protecting against unauthorized remote access.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] One way to identify weaknesses in access controls is to bring in a hacker to try and crack one's system by either gaining entry to the building and using an internal terminal or hacking in from the outside through remote access.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] An information security audit can be defined by examining the different aspects of information security.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] External and internal professionals within an institution have the responsibility of maintaining and inspecting the adequacy and effectiveness of information security.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] As in any institution, there are various controls to be implemented and maintained.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] To secure the information, an institution is expected to apply security measures to circumvent outside intervention.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] By and large, the two concepts of application security and segregation of duties are both in many ways connected, and they both have the same goal: to protect the integrity of the company's data and to prevent fraud.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] For application security, it has to do with preventing unauthorized access to hardware and software through having proper security measures both physical and electronic in place.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] With segregation of duties, it is primarily a physical review of individuals' access to the systems and processing and ensuring that there are no overlaps that could lead to fraud.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/information-security-audit] The type of audit the individual performs determines the specific procedures and tests to be executed throughout the audit process.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] In computer log management and intelligence, **log analysis** (or *system and network log analysis*) is an art and science seeking to make sense of computer-generated records (also called log or audit trail records).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] The process of creating such records is called data logging.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] Logs are emitted by network devices, operating systems, applications and all manner of intelligent or programmable devices.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] A stream of messages in time sequence often comprises a log.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] Logs may be directed to files and stored on disk or directed as a network stream to a log collector.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] Log messages must usually be interpreted concerning the internal state of its source (e.g., application) and announce security-relevant or operations-relevant events (e.g., a user login, or a systems error).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] Logs are often created by software developers to aid in the debugging of the operation of an application or understanding how users are interacting with a system, such as a search engine.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] The syntax and semantics of data within log messages are usually application or vendor-specific.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] The terminology may also vary; for example, the authentication of a user to an application may be described as a log in, a logon, a user connection or an authentication event.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] Hence, log analysis must interpret messages within the context of an application, vendor, system or configuration to make useful comparisons to messages from different log sources.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] Log message format or content may not always be fully documented.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] A task of the log analyst is to induce the system to emit the full range of messages to understand the complete domain from which the messages must be interpreted.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] A log analyst may map varying terminology from different log sources into a uniform, normalized terminology so that reports and statistics can be derived from a heterogeneous environment.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] For example, log messages from Windows, Unix, network firewalls, and databases may be aggregated into a "normalized" report for the auditor.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] Different systems may signal different message priorities with a different vocabulary, such as "error" and "warning" vs.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] Hence, log analysis practices exist on the continuum from text retrieval to reverse engineering of software.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] Log Analysis is often compared to other analytics tools such as application performance management (APM) and error monitoring.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] While much of their functionality is clear overlap, the difference is rooted in process.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] APM has an emphasis on performance and is utilized most in production.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/log-analysis] Error monitoring is driven by developers versus operations, and integrates into code in exception handling blocks.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] In general, **compliance** means conforming to a rule, such as a specification, policy, standard or law.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Compliance has traditionally been explained by reference to deterrence theory, according to which punishing a behavior will decrease the violations both by the wrongdoer (specific deterrence) and by others (general deterrence).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] This view has been supported by economic theory, which has framed punishment in terms of costs and has explained compliance in terms of a cost-benefit equilibrium (Becker 1968).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] However, psychological research on motivation provides an alternative view: granting rewards (Deci, Koestner and Ryan, 1999) or imposing fines (Gneezy Rustichini 2000) for a certain behavior is a form of extrinsic motivation that weakens intrinsic motivation and ultimately undermines compliance.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Regulations and accrediting organizations vary among fields, with examples such as PCI-DSS and GLBA in the financial industry, FISMA for U.S. federal agencies, HACCP for the food and beverage industry, and the Joint Commission and HIPAA in healthcare.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] In some cases other compliance frameworks (such as COBIT) or even standards (NIST) inform on how to comply with regulations.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Some organizations keep compliance data—all data belonging or pertaining to the enterprise or included in the law, which can be used for the purpose of implementing or validating compliance—in a separate store for meeting reporting requirements.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Compliance software is increasingly being implemented to help companies manage their compliance data more efficiently.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] This store may include calculations, data transfers, and audit trails.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The ISO also produces international standards such as ISO/IEC 27002 to help organizations meet regulatory compliance with their security management and assurance best practices.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Some local or international specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) also develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] They thereby provide a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the products to safety, security or design standards.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance varies not only by industry but often by location.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The financial, research, and pharmaceutical regulatory structures in one country, for example, may be similar but with particularly different nuances in another country.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] These similarities and differences are often a product "of reactions to the changing objectives and requirements in different countries, industries, and policy contexts".
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] These regulators help to ensure financial institutes meet their promises, that transactional information is well documented, and that competition is fair while protecting consumers.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Australian organisations seeking to remain compliant with various regulations may turn to AS ISO 19600:2015 (which supersedes AS 3806-2006).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] This standard helps organisations with compliance management, placing "emphasis on the organisational elements that are required to support compliance" while also recognizing the need for continual improvement.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] In Canada, federal regulation of deposits, insurance, and superannuation is governed by two independent bodies: the OSFI through the Bank Act, and FINTRAC, mandated by the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act, 2001 (PCMLTFA).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] These groups protect consumers, regulate how risk is controlled and managed, and investigate illegal action such as money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] On a provincial level, each province maintain individuals laws and agencies.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Unlike any other major federation, Canada does not have a securities regulatory authority at the federal government level.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The provincial and territorial regulators work together to coordinate and harmonize regulation of the Canadian capital markets through the Canadian Securities Administrators (CSA).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Other key regulators in Canada include the Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) for food safety, animal health, and plant health; Health Canada for public health; and Environment and Climate Change Canada for environment and sustainable energy.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] For more industry specific guidance, e.g., financial institutions, Canada's E-13 Regulatory Compliance Management provides specific compliance risk management tactics.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance in the European Union (EU) is governed by a harmonized legal framework designed to ensure consistency across member states while allowing for national implementation.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] EU compliance regulations cover various industries, including consumer product safety, financial services, environmental protection, and data privacy.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR) establishes a unified safety framework for consumer products across the EU, requiring manufacturers to conduct risk assessments, maintain traceability documentation, and meet safety compliance standards before placing products on the market.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The GPSR applies to all consumer products made available in the EU unless covered by sector-specific regulations, such as medical devices or food products.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The regulation extends to products sold through e-commerce platforms, requiring online marketplaces to ensure that only compliant products are listed.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Fulfillment service providers are also included as economic operators, making them responsible for product safety compliance in certain cases.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] For business compliance, the EU’s regulatory approach is guided by the New Legislative Framework (NLF) and various sector-specific directives and regulations.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Businesses must comply with EU product conformity assessments and affix the CE marking to indicate compliance with essential safety and performance standards.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Financial compliance is enforced through regulations such as the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II) and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which set strict requirements for financial transparency, consumer protection, and data security.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The EU Legislation Compliance framework ensures that organizations operate within the legal boundaries of EU directives, helping public and private entities manage regulatory risks efficiently.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Companies operating in the EU must stay updated on evolving compliance requirements, as non-compliance can lead to fines, product recalls, or restrictions on market access.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The financial sector in the Netherlands is heavily regulated.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The Dutch Central Bank (De Nederlandsche Bank N.V.) is the prudential regulator while the Netherlands Authority for Financial Markets (AFM) is the regulator for behavioral supervision of financial institutions and markets.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] In India, compliance regulation takes place across three strata: Central, State, and Local regulation.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] India veers towards central regulation, especially of financial organizations and foreign funds.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Compliance regulations vary based on the industry segment in addition to the geographical mix.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Most regulation comes in the following broad categories: economic regulation, regulation in the public interest, and environmental regulation.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] India has also been characterized by poor compliance - reports suggest that only around 65% of companies are fully compliant to norms.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The Monetary Authority of Singapore is Singapore's central bank and financial regulatory authority.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] It administers the various statutes pertaining to money, banking, insurance, securities and the financial sector in general, as well as currency issuance.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] There is considerable regulation in the United Kingdom, some of which is derived from European Union legislation.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Various areas are policed by different bodies, such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), Environment Agency, Scottish Environment Protection Agency, Information Commissioner's Office, Care Quality Commission, and others: see List of regulators in the United Kingdom.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Important compliance issues for all organizations large and small include the Data Protection Act 2018 and, for the public sector, Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Corporate scandals and breakdowns such as the Enron case of reputational risk in 2001 have increased calls for stronger compliance and regulations, particularly for publicly listed companies.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) is an agency of the United States Department of the Treasury under the auspices of the Under Secretary of the Treasury for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] OFAC administers and enforces economic and trade sanctions based on U.S. foreign policy and national security goals against targeted foreign states, organizations, and individuals.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in the U.S. generally means compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] These laws and regulations can have criminal or civil penalties.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The definition of what constitutes an effective compliance plan has been elusive.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Most authors, however, continue to cite the guidance provided by the United States Sentencing Commission in Chapter 8 of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Small Business Administration re-launched Business.gov (later Business.USA.gov and finally SBA.Gov) which provides a single point of access to government services and information that help businesses comply with government regulations.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Department of Labor, Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) was created by Congress to assure safe and healthful working conditions for working men and women by setting and enforcing standards and by providing training, outreach, education, and assistance.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] OSHA implements laws and regulations regularly in the following areas, construction, maritime, agriculture, and recordkeeping.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The United States Department of Transportation also has various laws and regulations requiring that prime contractors when bidding on federally funded projects engage in good faith effort compliance, meaning they must document their outreach to certified disadvantaged business enterprises.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Data retention is a part of regulatory compliance that is proving to be a challenge in many instances.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The security that comes from compliance with industry regulations can seem contrary to maintaining user privacy.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Data retention laws and regulations ask data owners and other service providers to retain extensive records of user activity beyond the time necessary for normal business operations.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] These requirements have been called into question by privacy rights advocates.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in this area is becoming very difficult.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Laws like the CAN-SPAM Act and Fair Credit Reporting Act in the U.S. require that businesses give people the right to be forgotten.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] In other words, they must remove individuals from marketing lists if it is requested, tell them when and why they might share personal information with a third party, or at least ask permission before sharing that data.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Now, with new laws coming out that demand longer data retention despite the individual’s desires, it can create some real difficulties.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Money laundering and terrorist financing pose significant threats to the integrity of the financial system and national security.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] To combat these threats, the EU has adopted a risk-based approach to Anti-Money Laundering and Combating the Financing of Terrorism (AML/CFT) that relies on cooperation and coordination between EU and national authorities.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] In this context, risk-based regulation refers to the approach of identifying and assessing potential risks of money laundering and terrorist financing and implementing regulatory measures proportional to those risks.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] However, the shared enforcement powers between EU and national authorities in the implementation and enforcement of AML/CFT regulations can create legal implications and challenges.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] The potential for inconsistent application of AML regulations across different jurisdictions can create regulatory arbitrage and undermine the effectiveness of AML efforts.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Additionally, a lack of clear and consistent legal frameworks defining the roles and responsibilities of EU and national authorities in AML enforcement can lead to situations where accountability is difficult to establish.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Corporate Governance Code (formerly the Combined Code) is issued by the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) and "sets standards of good practice in relation to board leadership and effectiveness, remuneration, accountability, and relations with shareholders".
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] All companies with a Premium Listing of equity shares in the U.K. are required under the Listing Rules to report on how they have applied the Combined Code in their annual report and accounts.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] It further demonstrates the relationship that subsists among shareholders, management, and the independent audit teams.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] Financial statements must be prepared using a particular set of rules and regulations hence the rationale behind allowing the companies to apply the provisions of company law, international financial reporting standards (IFRS), as well as the U.K. stock exchange rules as directed by the FCA.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/regulatory-compliance] It is also possible that shareholders may not understand the figures as presented in the various financial statements, hence it is critical that the board should provide notes on accounting policies as well as other explanatory notes to help them understand the report better.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM tools can be implemented as software, hardware, or managed services.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems log security events and generate reports to meet regulatory frameworks such as the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) and the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] The integration of SIM and SEM within SIEM provides organizations with a centralized approach for monitoring security events and responding to threats in real-time.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] In recent years, SIEM has become increasingly incorporated into national cybersecurity initiatives.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] For instance, Executive Order 14028 signed in 2021 by U.S.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] President Joseph Biden mandates the use of SIEM technologies to improve incident detection and reporting in federal systems.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Compliance with these mandates is further reinforced by frameworks such as NIST SP 800-92, which outlines best practices for managing computer security logs.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Modern SIEM platforms are aggregating and normalizing data not only from various Information Technology (IT) sources, but from production and manufacturing Operational Technology (OT) environments as well.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Initially, system logging was primarily used for troubleshooting and debugging.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] However, as operating systems and networks have grown more complex, so has the generation of system logs.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] The monitoring of system logs has also become increasingly common due to the rise of sophisticated cyberattacks and the need for compliance with regulatory frameworks, which mandate logging security controls within risk management frameworks (RMF).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Starting in the late 1970s, working groups began establishing criteria for managing auditing and monitoring programs, laying the groundwork for modern cybersecurity practices, such as insider threat detection and incident response.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] A key publication during this period was NIST’s Special Publication 500-19.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] In 2005, the term "SIEM" (Security Information and Event Management) was introduced by Gartner analysts Mark Nicolett and Amrit Williams.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems provide a single interface for gathering security data from information systems and presenting it as actionable intelligence.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] With the implementation of RMFs globally, auditing and monitoring have become central to information assurance and security.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Cybersecurity professionals now rely on logging data to perform real-time security functions, driven by governance models that incorporate these processes into analytical tasks.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] As information assurance matured in the late 1990s and into the 2000s, the need to centralize system logs became apparent.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Centralized log management allows for easier oversight and coordination across networked systems.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] President Joseph Biden signed Executive Order 14028, "Improving the Nation's Cybersecurity," which established further logging requirements, including audit logging and endpoint protection, to enhance incident response capabilities.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] This order was a response to an increase in ransomware attacks targeting critical infrastructure.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] By reinforcing information assurance controls within RMFs, the order aimed to drive compliance and secure funding for cybersecurity initiatives.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Published in September 2006, the NIST SP 800-92 Guide to Computer Security Log Management serves as a key document within the NIST Risk Management Framework to guide what should be auditable.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] As indicated by the absence of the term "SIEM", the document was released before the widespread adoption of SIEM technologies.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Although the guide is not exhaustive due to rapid changes in technology since its publication, it remains relevant by anticipating industry growth.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] NIST is not the only source of guidance on regulatory mechanisms for auditing and monitoring, and many organizations are encouraged to adopt SIEM solutions rather than relying solely on host-based checks.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Public and private organizations frequently reference NIST documents in their security policies.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] NIST SP 800-53 AU-2 Event Monitoring is a key security control that supports system auditing and ensures continuous monitoring for information assurance and cybersecurity operations.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM solutions are typically employed as central tools for these efforts.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Federal systems categorized based on their impact on confidentiality, integrity, and availability (CIA) have five specific logging requirements (AU-2 a-e) that must be met.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] While logging every action is possible, it is generally not recommended due to the volume of logs and the need for actionable security data.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] AU-2 provides a foundation for organizations to build a logging strategy that aligns with other controls.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] NIST SP 800-53 SI-4 System Monitoring outlines the requirements for monitoring systems, including detecting unauthorized access and tracking anomalies, malware, and potential attacks.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] This security control specifies both the hardware and software requirements for detecting suspicious activities.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Similarly, NIST SP 800-53 RA-10 Threat Hunting, added in Revision 5, emphasizes proactive network defense by identifying threats that evade traditional controls.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM solutions play a critical role in aggregating security information for threat hunting teams.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Together, AU-2, SI-4, and RA-10 demonstrate how NIST controls integrate into a comprehensive security strategy.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] These controls, supported by SIEM solutions, help ensure continuous monitoring, risk assessments, and in-depth defense mechanisms across federal and private networks.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] In practice many products in this area will have a mix of these functions, so there will often be some overlap – and many commercial vendors also promote their own terminology.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Oftentimes commercial vendors provide different combinations of these functionalities which tend to improve SIEM overall.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Log management alone doesn't provide real-time insights on network security, SEM on its own won't provide complete data for deep threat analysis.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] When SEM and log management are combined, more information is available for SIEM to monitor.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] A key focus is to monitor and help manage user and service privileges, directory services and other system-configuration changes; as well as providing log auditing and review and incident response.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM architectures may vary by vendor; however, generally, essential components comprise the SIEM engine.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] A basic SIEM infrastructure is depicted in the image to the right.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Computer security researcher Chris Kubecka identified the following SIEM use cases, presented at the hacking conference 28C3 (Chaos Communication Congress).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Modern SIEM platforms support not only detection, but response too.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] The response can be manual or automated including AI based response.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems play a significant role in helping organizations meet regulatory compliance requirements by centralizing log collection, enabling real-time monitoring, and generating audit-ready reports.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Under the HIPAA Security Rule, covered entities must implement audit controls that record and examine activity in information systems containing electronic protected health information (ePHI).
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would require covered entities to deploy technology capable of detecting and responding to security incidents within 24 hours, a capability commonly provided by SIEM platforms.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 10 mandates that organizations track and monitor all access to network resources and cardholder data, with SIEM systems commonly used to aggregate and analyze the required log data across distributed environments.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Similarly, the Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX) requires organizations to maintain audit trails for financial system access, and SIEM platforms provide the centralized logging and retention capabilities necessary to demonstrate compliance during audits.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] SIEM systems can have hundreds and thousands of correlation rules.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Some of these are simple, and some are more complex.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Once a correlation rule is triggered the system can take appropriate steps to mitigate a cyber attack.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Usually, this includes sending a notification to a user and then possibly limiting or even shutting down the system.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Brute force detection is relatively straightforward.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Brute forcing relates to continually trying to guess a variable.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] It most commonly refers to someone trying to constantly guess your password - either manually or with a tool.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] However, it can refer to trying to guess URLs or important file locations on your system.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] An automated brute force is easy to detect as someone trying to enter their password 60 times in a minute is impossible.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] When a user logs in to a system, generally speaking, it creates a timestamp of the event.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Alongside the time, the system may often record other useful information such as the device used, physical location, IP address, incorrect login attempts, etc.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] The more data is collected the more use can be gathered from it.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] For impossible travel, the system looks at the current and last login date/time and the difference between the recorded distances.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] If it deems it's not possible for this to happen, for example traveling hundreds of miles within a minute, then it will set off a warning.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Many employees and users are now using VPN services which may obscure physical location.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] This should be taken into consideration when setting up such a rule.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] The average user does not typically copy or move files on the system repeatedly.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Thus, any excessive file copying on a system could be attributed to an attacker wanting to cause harm to an organization.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Unfortunately, it's not as simple as stating someone has gained access to your network illegally and wants to steal confidential information.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] It could also be an employee looking to sell company information, or they could just want to take home some files for the weekend.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Monitoring network traffic against unusual patterns that includes any threats or attacks ranging from DDOS to network scans.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Note SIEM can monitor data flow in the network and to detect and prevent potential data exfiltration efforts.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] In general dedicated Data loss prevention (DLP) take care about data loss prevention.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] A DDoS (distributed denial of service) attack could cause significant damage to a company or organization.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] A DDoS attack can not only take a website offline, it can also make a system weaker.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] With suitable correlation rules in place, a SIEM should trigger an alert at the start of the attack so that the company can take the necessary precautionary measures to protect vital systems.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] File integrity and change monitoring (FIM) is the process of monitoring the files on your system.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Unexpected changes in your system files will trigger an alert as it's a likely indication of a cyber attack.
[src:aws-cloudtrail/security-information-and-event-management] Some examples of customized rules to alert on event conditions involve user authentication rules, attacks detected and infections detected.
